{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778108302,"nonce":"eWkRiqtquege0jCClK2LKhoViBg=","message":"## Riccati Q,R faithful test: substantive finding (xfail)\n\nThe C\u0026S Eq. 15 Q,R reproduction merged via `cd229998` is **xfailed** with a substantive diagnosis: Q-shape is NOT the variable explaining our negative Δv on the C\u0026S plant.\n\n| Q,R schedule | Plant | Δv at 1.5γ* |\n|---|---|---|\n| Faithful C\u0026S Eq. 15 | C\u0026S (k=0.1) | **−0.04%** |\n| rlrmp Q,R | C\u0026S (k=0.1) | −0.77% |\n| rlrmp Q,R | rlrmp (k=10) | +10.8% |\n\n**Implication: production Riccati's disturbance channel is most likely flavor-(a), not flavor-(b).** Production's `B_w` is an additive-force disturbance (force enters via the force channel of the augmented state). C\u0026S 2019 used `ΔA·x·dt + C·dw` — a structural model-class perturbation acting on the plant matrix. If production is solving flavor-(a) H∞ while C\u0026S solved flavor-(b), no Q,R schedule will close the gap; the disturbance channel formulation needs to change.\n\n**Where this lives going forward:** this is a *training-method / mathematical-model* concern, not strictly an analysis concern. Once `coordination/training-methods` is in place, future cross-cutting comments about Riccati / disturbance channels / flavor-of-max should land there. For now, posting here because `4d38c15` is the operative coordination issue.\n\n**Tied to:** `c723082` (LinearDynamicsAdversary — the flavor-(b) lift on the training side; the analogous Riccati-side lift would extend the production module's `B_w` to support `ΔA`-style structural disturbance). The xfailed test in `tests/test_hinf_riccati.py::test_cs_faithful_qr_velocity_inflation` documents the open question with the full diagnosis embedded in its xfail reason string.","files":null}]}